    "title": "into",
    "description": "Set theory is the study of collections of distinct, well-defined objects, called elements or members. The theory was founded by the German mathematician Georg Cantor. In set theory, sets are usually denoted by capital letters, while their elements are represented by lowercase letters. The symbol \r\nÎ“ÃªÃª indicates membership (\"belongs to\"), and \r\nÎ“ÃªÃ« indicates nonÎ“Ã‡Ã¦membership (\"does not belong to\").\r\n\r\nThere are two common ways to represent a set:\r\n\r\nRoster (or tabular) form Î“Ã‡Ã¶ All elements are listed, separated by commas, and enclosed in curly braces. The order of elements does not matter, and repetition is typically avoided.\r\nExample: {2,4,6,8}\r\n\r\nRule (or setÎ“Ã‡Ã¦builder) form Î“Ã‡Ã¶ A set is described by a common property \r\np(x)\r\nthat all its elements (and only those elements) satisfy. This is written as \r\n{xÎ“ÃªÃºp(x) holds} or {x:p(x) holds}.\r\nExample: \r\n\r\n{xÎ“ÃªÃºx is an even positive integer less than 10}",
